{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28b333c46ffeUk02tKuCrqp97d","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d74ccd86b001r3Hw0FacPAXS4E","parts":[{"id":"prt_d74cce2b200185Y99ZYGmZYgo5","messageID":"msg_d74ccd86b001r3Hw0FacPAXS4E","sessionID":"ses_28b333c46ffeUk02tKuCrqp97d","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_dd6d47b6a8ae40088f4da9c7","state":{"status":"running","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst"},"time":{"start":1775781077971}}}]}
{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28b333c46ffeUk02tKuCrqp97d","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d74ccd86b001r3Hw0FacPAXS4E","parts":[{"id":"prt_d74cce2b200185Y99ZYGmZYgo5","messageID":"msg_d74ccd86b001r3Hw0FacPAXS4E","sessionID":"ses_28b333c46ffeUk02tKuCrqp97d","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_dd6d47b6a8ae40088f4da9c7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.rst</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: |github-actions| |coverage|\n2: \n3: About\n4: =====\n5: \n6: CAN BUS tools in Python 3.\n7: \n8: - `DBC`_, `KCD`_, SYM, ARXML 3&4 and CDD file parsing.\n9: \n10: - CAN message encoding and decoding.\n11: \n12: - Simple and extended signal multiplexing.\n13: \n14: - Diagnostic DID encoding and decoding.\n15: \n16: - ``candump`` output decoder.\n17: \n18: - Node `tester`_.\n19: \n20: - `C` source code generator.\n21: \n22: - CAN bus monitor.\n23: \n24: - Graphical plots of signals.\n25: \n26: Project homepage: https://github.com/cantools/cantools\n27: \n28: Documentation: https://cantools.readthedocs.io\n29: \n30: Installation\n31: ============\n32: \n33: .. code-block:: bash\n34: \n35:     python3 -m pip install cantools\n36: \n37: Example usage\n38: =============\n39: \n40: Scripting\n41: ---------\n42: \n43: The example starts by parsing a `small DBC-file`_ and printing its\n44: messages and signals.\n45: \n46: .. code-block:: python\n47: \n48:    >>> import cantools\n49:    >>> from pprint import pprint\n50:    >>> db = cantools.database.load_file('tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc')\n51:    >>> db.messages\n52:    [message('ExampleMessage', 0x1f0, False, 8, 'Example message used as template in MotoHawk models.')]\n53:    >>> example_message = db.get_message_by_name('ExampleMessage')\n54:    >>> pprint(example_message.signals)\n55:    [signal('Enable', 7, 1, 'big_endian', False, 1.0, 0, 0.0, 0.0, '-', False, None, {0: 'Disabled', 1: 'Enabled'}, None),\n56:     signal('AverageRadius', 6, 6, 'big_endian', False, 0.1, 0, 0.0, 5.0, 'm', False, None, None, ''),\n57:     signal('Temperature', 0, 12, 'big_endian', True, 0.01, 250, 229.53, 270.47, 'degK', False, None, None, None)]\n58: \n59: The example continues `encoding`_ a message and sending it on a CAN\n60: bus using the `python-can`_ package.\n61: \n62: .. code-block:: python\n63: \n64:    >>> import can\n65:    >>> can_bus = can.interface.Bus('vcan0', bustype='socketcan')\n66:    >>> data = example_message.encode({'Temperature': 250.1, 'AverageRadius': 3.2, 'Enable': 1})\n67:    >>> message = can.Message(arbitration_id=example_message.frame_id, is_extended_id=example_message.is_extended_frame, data=data)\n68:    >>> can_bus.send(message)\n69: \n70: Alternatively, a message can be encoded using the `encode_message()`_\n71: method on the database object.\n72: \n73: The last part of the example receives and `decodes`_ a CAN message.\n74: \n75: .. code-block:: python\n76: \n77:    >>> message = can_bus.recv()\n78:    >>> db.decode_message(message.arbitration_id, message.data)\n79:    {'AverageRadius': 3.2, 'Enable': 'Enabled', 'Temperature': 250.09}\n80: \n81: See `examples`_ for additional examples.\n82: \n83: Command line tool\n84: -----------------\n85: \n86: The decode subcommand\n87: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n88: \n89: Decode CAN frames captured with the Linux program ``candump``.\n90: \n91: .. code-block:: text\n92: \n93:    $ candump vcan0 | python3 -m cantools decode tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n94:      vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 ::\n95:    ExampleMessage(\n96:        Enable: 'Enabled' -,\n97:        AverageRadius: 0.0 m,\n98:        Temperature: 255.92 degK\n99:    )\n100:      vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 ::\n101:    ExampleMessage(\n102:        Enable: 'Enabled' -,\n103:        AverageRadius: 0.0 m,\n104:        Temperature: 255.92 degK\n105:    )\n106:      vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 ::\n107:    ExampleMessage(\n108:        Enable: 'Enabled' -,\n109:        AverageRadius: 0.0 m,\n110:        Temperature: 255.92 degK\n111:    )\n112: \n113: Alternatively, the decoded message can be printed on a single line:\n114: \n115: .. code-block:: text\n116: \n117:    $ candump vcan0 | python3 -m cantools decode --single-line tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n118:      vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 :: ExampleMessage(Enable: 'Enabled' -, AverageRadius: 0.0 m, Temperature: 255.92 degK)\n119:      vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 :: ExampleMessage(Enable: 'Enabled' -, AverageRadius: 0.0 m, Temperature: 255.92 degK)\n120:      vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 :: ExampleMessage(Enable: 'Enabled' -, AverageRadius: 0.0 m, Temperature: 255.92 degK)\n121: \n122: The plot subcommand\n123: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n124: \n125: The plot subcommand is similar to the decode subcommand but messages are visualized using `matplotlib`_ instead of being printed to stdout.\n126: \n127: .. code-block:: bash\n128: \n129:     $ candump -l vcan0\n130:     $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log\n131:     (1609779922.655421) vcan0 00000343#B204B9049C049C04\n132:     (1609779922.655735) vcan0 0000024A#120527052E051905\n133:     (1609779923.657524) vcan0 00000343#C404C404CB04C404\n134:     (1609779923.658086) vcan0 0000024A#8B058B058B059205\n135:     (1609779924.659912) vcan0 00000343#5C04790479045504\n136:     (1609779924.660471) vcan0 0000024A#44064B0659064406\n137:     (1609779925.662277) vcan0 00000343#15040704F203F203\n138:     (1609779925.662837) vcan0 0000024A#8B069906A706A706\n139:     (1609779926.664191) vcan0 00000343#BC03B503A703BC03\n140:     (1609779926.664751) vcan0 0000024A#A006A706C406C406\n141: \n142:     $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | python3 -m cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc\n143: \n144: .. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-1.png\n145: \n146: If you don't want to show all signals you can select the desired signals with command line arguments.\n147: A ``*`` can stand for any number of any character, a ``?`` for exactly one arbitrary character.\n148: Signals separated by a ``-`` are displayed in separate subplots.\n149: Optionally a format can be specified after a signal, separated by a colon.\n150: \n151: .. code-block:: bash\n152: \n153:     $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | python3 -m cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc '*33.*fl:-<' '*33.*fr:->' - '*33.*rl:-<' '*33.*rr:->'\n154: \n155: .. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-2-subplots.png\n156: \n157: Signals with a different range of values can be displayed in the same subplot on different vertical axes by separating them with a comma.\n158: \n159: .. code-block:: bash\n160: \n161:    $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | cantools plot --auto-color tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc -- \\\n162:       --ylabel 'Bremse 33' '*_33.*fl*:-<' '*_33.*fr*:>' '*_33.*rl*:3' '*_33.*rr*:4' , \\\n163:       --ylabel 'Bremse 2' '*_2.*fl*:-<' '*_2.*fr*:>' '*_2.*rl*:3' '*_2.*rr*:4'\n164: \n165: .. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-2-axes.png\n166: \n167: Matplotlib comes with different preinstalled styles that you can use:\n168: \n169: .. code-block:: bash\n170: \n171:    $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc --style seaborn\n172: \n173: .. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-seaborn.png\n174: \n175: You can try all available styles with\n176: \n177: .. code-block:: bash\n178: \n179:    $ cantools plot --list-styles . | sed -n '/^- /s/^- //p' | while IFS= read -r style; do\n180:          cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc --style \"$style\" --title \"--style '$style'\"\n181:      done\n182: \n183: For more information see\n184: \n185: .. code-block:: bash\n186: \n187:     $ python3 -m cantools plot --help\n188: \n189: Note that by default matplotlib is not installed with cantools. But it can be by specifying an extra\n190: at installation:\n191: \n192: .. code-block:: bash\n193: \n194:     $ python3 -m pip install cantools[plot]\n195: \n196: The dump subcommand\n197: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n198: \n199: Dump given database in a human readable format:\n200: \n201: .. code-block:: text\n202: \n203:    $ python3 -m cantools dump tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n204:    ================================= Messages =================================\n205: \n206:      ------------------------------------------------------------------------\n207: \n208:      Name:       ExampleMessage\n209:      Id:         0x1f0\n210:      Length:     8 bytes\n211:      Cycle time: - ms\n212:      Senders:    PCM1\n213:      Layout:\n214: \n215:                              Bit\n216: \n217:                 7   6   5   4   3   2   1   0\n218:               +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n219:             0 |<-x|<---------------------x|<--|\n220:               +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n221:                 |                       +-- AverageRadius\n222:                 +-- Enable\n223:               +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n224:             1 |-------------------------------|\n225:               +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n226:             2 |----------x|   |   |   |   |   |\n227:         B     +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n228:         y               +-- Temperature\n229:         t     +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n230:         e   3 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n231:               +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n232:             4 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n233:               +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n234:             5 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n235:               +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n236:             6 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n237:               +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n238:             7 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n239:               +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n240: \n241:      Signal tree:\n242: \n243:        -- {root}\n244:           +-- Enable\n245:           +-- AverageRadius\n246:           +-- Temperature\n247: \n248:      Signal choices:\n249: \n250:        Enable\n251:            0 Disabled\n252:            1 Enabled\n253: \n254:      ------------------------------------------------------------------------\n255: \n256: The list subcommand\n257: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n258: \n259: Print all information of a given database in a human readable\n260: format. This is very similar to the \"dump\" subcommand, but the output\n261: is less pretty, slightly more comprehensive and easier to parse by\n262: shell scripts:\n263: \n264: .. code-block:: bash\n265: \n266:     $ python3 -m cantools list -a tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n267:     ExampleMessage:\n268:       Comment[None]: Example message used as template in MotoHawk models.\n269:       Frame ID: 0x1f0 (496)\n270:       Size: 8 bytes\n271:       Is extended frame: False\n272:       Signals:\n273:         Enable:\n274:           Type: Integer\n275:           Start bit: 7\n276:           Length: 1 bits\n277:           Unit: -\n278:           Is signed: False\n279:           Named values:\n280:             0: Disabled\n281: \n282: The generate C source subcommand\n283: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n284: \n285: Generate `C` source code from given database.\n286: \n287: The generated code contains:\n288: \n289: - Message `structs`_.\n290: \n291: - Message `pack`_ and `unpack`_ functions.\n292: \n293: - Signal `encode`_ and `decode`_ functions.\n294: \n295: - Frame id, length, type, cycle time and signal choices `defines`_.\n296: \n297: Known limitations:\n298: \n299: - The maximum signal size is 64 bits, which in practice is never\n300:   exceeded.\n301: \n302: Below is an example of how to generate C source code from a\n303: database. The database is ``tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc``.\n304: \n305: .. code-block:: text\n306: \n307:    $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n308:    Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n309: \n310: See `motohawk.h`_ and `motohawk.c`_ for the contents of the generated\n311: files.\n312: \n313: In this example we use ``--use-float`` so floating point numbers in the generated\n314: code are single precision (``float``) instead of double precision (``double``).\n315: \n316: .. code-block:: text\n317: \n318:    $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source --use-float tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n319:    Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n320: \n321: In the next example we use ``--database-name`` to set a custom\n322: namespace for all generated types, defines and functions. The output\n323: file names are also changed by this option.\n324: \n325: .. code-block:: text\n326: \n327:    $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source --database-name my_database_name tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n328:    Successfully generated my_database_name.h and my_database_name.c.\n329: \n330: See `my_database_name.h`_ and `my_database_name.c`_ for the contents\n331: of the generated files.\n332: \n333: In the next example we use ``--no-floating-point-numbers`` to generate\n334: code without floating point types, i.e. ``float`` and ``double``.\n335: \n336: .. code-block:: text\n337: \n338:    $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source --no-floating-point-numbers tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n339:    Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n340: \n341: See `motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.h`_ and\n342: `motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.c`_ for the contents of the\n343: generated files.\n344: \n345: In the last example ``--node`` is used to generate\n346: message pack functions only for messages sent by the specified node and unpack\n347: functions only for messages with its signal receivers belonging to that node. \n348: \n349: .. code-block:: text\n350: \n351:    $ cantools generate_c_source tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc --node PCM1\n352:    Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n353: \n354: See `motohawk_sender_node.h`_ and\n355: `motohawk_sender_node.c`_ for the contents of the\n356: generated files.\n357: \n358: Other C code generators:\n359: \n360: - http://www.coderdbc.com\n361: \n362: - https://github.com/howerj/dbcc\n363: \n364: - https://github.com/lonkamikaze/hsk-libs/blob/master/scripts/dbc2c.awk\n365: \n366: - https://sourceforge.net/projects/comframe/\n367: \n368: The monitor subcommand\n369: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n370: \n371: Monitor CAN bus traffic in a text based user interface.\n372: \n373: .. code-block:: text\n374: \n375:    $ python3 -m cantools monitor tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n376: \n377: .. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/monitor.png\n378: \n379: The menu at the bottom of the monitor shows the available commands.\n380: \n381: - Quit: Quit the monitor. Ctrl-C can be used as well.\n382: \n383: - Filter: Only display messages or signals matching given regular\n384:   expression. Press <Enter> to return to the menu from the filter\n385:   input line.\n386: \n387: - Play/Pause: Toggle between playing and paused (or running and freezed).\n388: \n389: - Reset: Reset the monitor to its initial state.\n390: \n391: Contributing\n392: ============\n393: \n394: #. Fork the repository.\n395: \n396: #. Install prerequisites. You can skip this if you use `tox`_.\n397: \n398:    .. code-block:: text\n399: \n400:       python3 -m pip install -e .[dev]\n401: \n402: #. Implement the new feature or bug fix.\n403: \n404: #. Implement test case(s) to ensure that future changes do not break\n405:    legacy.\n406: \n407: #. Run the linters\n408: \n409:    .. code-block:: text\n410: \n411:       ruff check src\n412:       mypy src\n413: \n414:    or\n415: \n416:    .. code-block:: text\n417: \n418:       tox -e ruff\n419:       tox -e mypy\n420: \n421: #. Run the tests.\n422: \n423:    .. code-block:: text\n424: \n425:       tox -e py\n426: \n427: #. Check test coverage.\n428: \n429:    .. code-block:: text\n430: \n431:       tox -e cov\n432:       firefox htmlcov/index.html\n433: \n434: #. Create a pull request.\n435: \n436: .. |github-actions| image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/actions/workflows/pythonpackage.yml/badge.svg?branch=master\n437:    :target: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/actions/workflows/pythonpackage.yml\n438:    :alt: Github Actions workflow status\n439: \n440: .. |coverage| image:: https://coveralls.io/repos/github/cantools/cantools/badge.svg?branch=master\n441:    :target: https://coveralls.io/github/cantoolscantools?branch=master\n442:    :alt: Test coverage reports on Coveralls.io\n443: \n444: \n445: .. _small DBC-file: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n446: \n447: .. _motohawk.dbc: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n448: \n449: .. _python-can: https://python-can.readthedocs.io/en/master/\n450: \n451: .. _DBC: http://www.socialledge.com/sjsu/index.php?title=DBC_Format\n452: \n453: .. _KCD: https://github.com/julietkilo/kcd\n454: \n455: .. _tester: http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.tester.Tester\n456: \n457: .. _encoding: http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.database.can.Message.encode\n458: \n459: .. _encode_message(): http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.database.can.Database.encode_message\n460: \n461: .. _decodes: http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.database.can.Database.decode_message\n462: \n463: .. _examples: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/examples\n464: \n465: .. _structs: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L58\n466: \n467: .. _pack: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L88\n468: \n469: .. _unpack: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L102\n470: \n471: .. _encode: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L116\n472: \n473: .. _decode: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L125\n474: \n475: .. _defines: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L42\n476: \n477: .. _motohawk.h: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h\n478: \n479: .. _motohawk.c: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.c\n480: \n481: .. _my_database_name.h: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/my_database_name.h\n482: \n483: .. _my_database_name.c: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/my_database_name.c\n484: \n485: .. _motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.h: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.h\n486: \n487: .. _motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.c: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.c\n488: \n489: .. _motohawk_sender_node.h: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk_sender_node.h\n490: \n491: .. _motohawk_sender_node.c: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk_sender_node.c\n492: \n493: .. _matplotlib: https://matplotlib.org/\n494: \n495: .. _tox: http://tox.readthedocs.org/\n\n(End of file - total 495 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"|github-actions| |coverage|\n\nAbout\n=====\n\nCAN BUS tools in Python 3.\n\n- `DBC`_, `KCD`_, SYM, ARXML 3&4 and CDD file parsing.\n\n- CAN message encoding and decoding.\n\n- Simple and extended signal multiplexing.\n\n- Diagnostic DID encoding and decoding.\n\n- ``candump`` output decoder.\n\n- Node `tester`_.\n\n- `C` source code generator.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.rst","time":{"start":1775781077971,"end":1775781077977}}}]}
